<H2><U>
<a name="figures">Important Chilcotin Mythological Figures</a>
</u></H2>

<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><A href="http://www.native-languages.org/northwest-raven.htm">Raven</a></font></U></B></I>: 
Raven is the culture hero of the Chilcotin and other Northwest Coast tribes.
He is a benevolent, respected figure who helps the people by bringing them sunlight and salmon,
but at the same time, he is also a trickster character and many Raven stories have to do with
his frivolous or poorly thought out behavior getting him into trouble.

<H2><U>
<a name="tribes">Chilcotin Indian Folklore</a>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.native-languages.org/chilcotinstory.htm
">The Stretching Tree</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Chilcotin legend about a faithful wife.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/The_White_Cat-Chilcotin.html
">The White Cat</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Chilcotin adaptation of a European legend.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20130203094420/http://www.talesunlimited.com/fulltext_test2.aspx?taleid=1435
">The Conquering Gambler</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Chilcotin story about two men who made unwise gambles.
<BR>

